# üåê HTTPD (Apache Web Server) ‚Äì Quick Notes

## 1Ô∏è‚É£ Purpose of HTTPD
- **HTTPD (Apache)** is the service/software that serves web pages over HTTP.
- Used for hosting websites (personal, business, profile, etc.).
- Instead of paying for hosting (GoDaddy, Wix, etc.), you can host on your own server.

---

## 2Ô∏è‚É£ Main Components & Files

| Path / Command | Purpose |
|----------------|---------|
| `/etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf` | Main **Apache configuration file** (port, docroot, user dirs, etc.) |
| `/var/www/html/index.html` | Default **homepage** file |
| `/var/log/httpd/` | Apache log directory (error & access logs) |
| `systemctl start|stop|restart httpd` | Start/stop/restart the Apache service |
| `systemctl enable httpd` | Auto-start Apache on boot |

---

## 3Ô∏è‚É£ Installation
```bash
# Install Apache (RHEL/CentOS)
sudo yum install httpd -y
# or
sudo dnf install httpd -y

    Dependencies like httpd-tools get installed automatically.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Config File Basics (httpd.conf)

    Comments start with #.

    Listen ‚Üí defines port (default HTTP = 80, HTTPS = 443).

    DocumentRoot ‚Üí default directory for site files (default /var/www/html).

    Can customize many settings (ports, permissions, virtual hosts, etc.).

5Ô∏è‚É£ Creating Your First Page

cd /var/www/html

# Create or edit homepage
vi index.html

Example:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body style="background-color:lightgrey;">
<br>
<h1 style="text-align:center;">Welcome to my first page</h1>
<h4>My name is Your Name</h4>
</body>
</html>

6Ô∏è‚É£ Start & Enable Service

sudo systemctl start httpd
sudo systemctl enable httpd
sudo systemctl status httpd

7Ô∏è‚É£ Access the Page

    Use your server‚Äôs IP in a browser:

    http://<server-ip>

    No DNS? Access directly via IP (e.g., 192.168.1.12).

8Ô∏è‚É£ Firewall Considerations

    Apache listens on port 80 by default.

    Allow traffic or temporarily disable firewall for testing:

# Stop firewall (testing only!)
sudo systemctl stop firewalld

# OR allow port 80 (permanent, safer)
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=http
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

9Ô∏è‚É£ Logs & Troubleshooting

    Error log: /var/log/httpd/error_log

    Access log: /var/log/httpd/access_log

    Check if service is running:

sudo systemctl status httpd

    Confirm firewall allows port 80.

üîü Quick Workflow Recap

    Install httpd.

    Edit /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf if needed.

    Put your index.html in /var/www/html.

    Open port 80 in firewall.

    Start and enable httpd.

    Test via browser using server‚Äôs IP.

üí° Tip: Every time you change HTML, refresh browser (F5). For config changes, restart Apache:

sudo systemctl restart httpd